==Notable events== Acquinity Sport's debut event was held on January 7, 2012 at [[Hollywood, Florida|Hollywood]]’s Westin Diplomat Resort and Spa, and was featured as the season opener of [[Telefutura]]'s Solo Boxeo series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/ed-paredes-looks-put-on-show-turning-stone--68524 |title=Ed Paredes Looks To Put on a Show at Turning Stone - Boxing News |publisher=Boxingscene.com |date=2013-08-23 |accessdate=2013-09-15}}</ref> Its second major event, branded "D-Day, Dominican Domination" aired on ESPN 2's Friday Night Fights on March 2, 2012, and featured headliner Joan "Baby Tyson" Guzman, who had recently signed on with Acquinity Sports. On November 30, 2012, Acquinity and bsavings.com presented a combination boxing-music event. Dubbed "Beatdown 2012," it featured a championship fight between Guzman and Khabib Allakhverdiev, followed by musical performances by [[Fabolous]], [[Flo Rida]], [[Waka Flocka]], [[DMX (rapper)|DMX]], [[Travis Porter]] and [[Fat Joe]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Anthony Hernandez |url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/2012-11-29/music/beatdown-2012-at-bb-amp-t-center-november-30/full/ |title=Beatdown 2012 at BB&T Center November 30 - - Music - Miami |publisher=Miami New Times |date=2012-11-29 |accessdate=2013-09-15}}</ref>
==Name change== In 2013 Acquinity CEO Garry Jonas and former heavyweight champion Mike Tyson partnered and formed Iron Mike Productions. This marked the hall-of-famer's return to boxing since his last appearance in the ring in 2005. The new promotion company's debut will take place on August 23, 2013 at the Turning Stone Resort Casino in [[Verona, New York]], and will be broadcast live on ESPN2's ''Friday Night Fights''.{{Update after|2015|3|8}}
