{{Infobox Film Festival | name = Reel Shorts Film Festival | host = Reel Shorts Film Society | number = 80+ | location = [[Grande Prairie]], [[Alberta]], [[Canada]] | language = International | website = http://reelshorts.ca }} The '''Reel Shorts Film Festival''', held annually in [[Grande Prairie]], [[Alberta]] since 2007, is recognized as one of North America's best short film festivals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://audnews.com/north-americas-best-short-film-festivals/|title=North America's Best Short Film Festivals|date=2014-07-31|work=AudNews|access-date=2017-09-10|language=en-US}}</ref> Its programming focus is [[Short film|short-form cinematic storytelling]], screening "gems of storytelling brilliance" from around the world, across Canada, and in the [[Peace River Country|Peace Region]].<ref>"About Reel Shorts", Reel Shorts Film Festival, retrieved Jan 6, 2013</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailyheraldtribune.com/2015/03/26/reel-shorts-shattering-records|title=Reel Shorts shattering records|last=Turner|first=Jocelyn|date=March 26, 2015|website=Daily Herald Tribune|language=en-CA|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-01-01}}</ref> The purpose is twofold: to entertain, educate, and engage audiences; and to grow the film-making community in the Peace Region by inspiring, developing, and showcasing its filmmakers. Thousands of submissions are received annually<ref>{{Cite book|title=So, You Want to Start a Film Festival: Conversations With Top Festival Creators|last=Gann|first=Jon|publisher=ReelPlan Press|year=2015|isbn=9781519166654|location=Washington, DC|pages=150-151}}</ref> from which 80-105 short films are selected.<ref name=":0" /> It is a qualifying festival for the [[Canadian Screen Awards]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailyheraldtribune.com/2013/08/29/reel-shorts-film-festival-receives-acct-accreditation|title=Reel Shorts Film Festival receives ACCT accreditation|last=Goruk|first=Kirsten|date=August 29, 2013|work=Daily Herald Tribune|access-date=September 10, 2017|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref>
== History == Terry Scerbak founded the festival as a production of the nonprofit [http://gplt.ca/ Grande Prairie Live Theatre] in 2007.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.artofthepeace.ca/magazine/8|title=Magazine {{!}} Art of the Peace|last=http://imagedesignpros.com|first=Image Design Professionals Inc. {{!}}|date=|work=Art of the Peace|access-date=2017-09-10|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|edition=Spring/Summer 2007|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2016, she was one of the founding members of the Reel Shorts Film Society which took over the production of the festival in 2017 with the full support and cooperation of the GPLT Board of Directors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailyheraldtribune.com/2017/01/05/reel-shorts-brings-award-winning-zombie-movie-to-gp|title=Reel Shorts brings award-winning zombie movie to GP|last=Rinne|first=Diana|date=January 5, 2017|website=Daily Herald Tribune|language=en-CA|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
The festival's program has grown from 3 days screening 38 films in 2007<ref>"About Reel Shorts", Reel Shorts Film Festival, retrieved Jan 6, 2013</ref> to 6-8 days screening 80-105 films since 2014.<ref name=":0">Mari Sasano, [https://albertaviews.ab.ca/2014/09/24/reeling-in-alberta/ "Reeling In Alberta"] [[Alberta Views]], Oct 2014</ref> The 12th edition of the festival will be May 8-14, 2018.
== Awards == Since 2010, audiences have determined the winner(s) of the Audience Choice Awards. Since 2014, the directors of Audience Choice Awards and Jury Awards have received an award designed by Grande Prairie sculptor Grant Berg.
